03887nam a22005895i 9780292769564DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211994txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927695647 a10.7560/7080822doi  a(DE-B1597)588649  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a942.011 aBlacker, Jean, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Faces of Time :bPortrayal of the Past in Old French and Latin Historical Narrative of the Anglo-Norman Regnum /cJean Blacker. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (279 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Task and Role of the Historian -- t2 Modes of Characterization: Images of the Kings -- t3 Patronage and Social Function: Users and Uses of History -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe twelfth century witnessed the sudden appearance and virtual disappearance of an important literary genre—the Old French verse chronicle. These poetic histories of the British kings, which today are treated as fiction, were written contemporaneously with Latin prose narratives, which are regarded as historical accounts. In this pathfinding study, however, Jean Blacker asserts that twelfth-century authors and readers viewed both genres as factual history. Blacker examines four Old French verse chronicles—Gaimar's Estoire des Engleis (c. 1135), Wace's Roman de Brut (c. 1155) and Roman de Rou (c. 1160–1174), and Benoît de Sainte-Maure's Chronique des Ducs de Normandie (c. 1174–1180) and four Latin narratives—William of Malmesbury's Gesta Regum (c. 1118–1143) and Historia Novella (c. 1140–1143), Orderic Vitalis's Historia Ecclesiastica (c. 1118–1140), and Geoffrey of Monmouth's Historia Regum Britanniae (c. 1138). She compares their similarity in three areas—the authors' stated intentions, their methods of characterization and narrative development, and the possible influences of patronage and audience expectation on the presentation of characters and events. This exploration reveals remarkable similarity among the texts, including their idealization of historical and even legendary figures, such as King Arthur. It opens fruitful lines of inquiry into the role these writers played in the creation of the Anglo-Norman regnum and suggests that the Old French verse chronicles filled political, psychic, and aesthetic needs unaddressed by Latin historical writing of the period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/70808240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292769564423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292769564/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK